\section{Classifying run events}

ProgSnap2 uses [[EventType]] and [[ProgramResult]] columns to
describe what happened.
Python blurs the compile/run distinction---a [[SyntaxError]] is
raised at import time, not during a separate compilation step---so
we use [[Run.Program]] for all executions, following the approach
used in existing ProgSnap2 Python datasets.

The [[ProgramResult]] is [[Success]] when the exit code is zero
and no exception occurred, [[Error]] when the exit code is
non-zero or an exception was raised, and empty when the data is
incomplete (crash with no trailer).

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def classify_run_result(run):
    """Classify a parsed run block's result.

    Returns ``"Success"``, ``"Error"``, or ``""`` (unknown,
    typically a crash).
    """
    if run["exit_code"] is None:
        return ""
    if run["exit_code"] == "0" \
            and run["exception_info"] is None:
        return "Success"
    return "Error"
@

<<progsnap2 test functions>>=
def test_classify_run_result_success():
    from learnlog.progsnap2 import classify_run_result
    run = {"exit_code": "0", "exception_info": None}
    assert classify_run_result(run) == "Success"

def test_classify_run_result_error():
    from learnlog.progsnap2 import classify_run_result
    run = {"exit_code": "1", "exception_info": "ValueError"}
    assert classify_run_result(run) == "Error"

def test_classify_run_result_crash():
    from learnlog.progsnap2 import classify_run_result
    run = {"exit_code": None, "exception_info": None}
    assert classify_run_result(run) == ""
